      {
        "id": "9zIq2wa9TdvdSZ1I",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Summarize (Orchestrating the Discussion)</strong></p><p><em>Discussing Solutions and Strategies</em></p><p>Have groups share how they connect the ratio to the diagrams to the percents.</p><p><strong>Suggested Questions</strong></p><ul><li>How do you represent 38 out of 50 on a bar diagram?</li><li>How do you represent 38 out of 50 on a 100 grid?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "RrZ9iOTxIfUoFwrf",
        "title": "Text 16",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>Some students might scale the ratio to 100 students first, then shade the bar. Others might say that every segment on the bar can represent 1/2 a student, so you shade in 2 partitions for each student.</li><li>Some students might want to use a grid of 50 rather than a grid of 100. Some might say that every student counts as 2 smaller squares, so you shade 2 for each student, or 76 squares. Others might change the ratio to 76 out of 100, then shade the grid. </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "KbWprg3XJYEAMfKX",
        "title": "Text 14",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><em>Making the Mathematics Explicit</em></p><p>After relating the comparison statements to the percent representation, students will see that a part-to-whole comparison where the total is 100 converts directly to a percentage.</p><p><strong>Suggested Questions</strong></p><ul><li>What would be a comparison statement and percent to describe What If...? Situation A Diagram A?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "WkPhPNjSC2tm7bj6",
        "title": "Text 15",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Various answers. An example might be &quot;For every 100 little squares, there are 30 pink, or 30% of the squares are pink.&quot; </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "NeZPF8u8A0PpQj-I",
        "title": "Text 18",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>What would be a comparison statement and percent to describe What If...? Situation A Diagram B? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6N5v3ZSWOWIYjFPk",
        "title": "Text 19",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Various answers. Students might say that for every 100 squares on the grid, 52 1/2 are pink, or 52.5% of the squares are pink.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
